WEBVTT

00:07.485 --> 00:10.358
- Often now, in my dying days,
I struggle with the notion

00:10.401 --> 00:15.058
of life after death.

00:15.102 --> 00:16.538
To those of faith,

00:16.581 --> 00:20.368
it's time eternal,
salvation.

00:20.411 --> 00:22.065
To those of science,

00:22.109 --> 00:25.590
it's merely the first tomorrow
after you die,

00:25.634 --> 00:27.984
a finite sentence
made meaningful

00:28.028 --> 00:31.379
by the question mark
at its conclusion,

00:31.422 --> 00:36.688
asking simply,
what have you left behind?

00:36.732 --> 00:39.430
- We think about the birth
of the universe as...

00:39.474 --> 00:40.997
the beginning of everything,
right?

00:41.041 --> 00:44.566
What without when,
planets without seconds.

00:44.609 --> 00:48.439
We have exhausted
the origins of the universe

00:48.483 --> 00:51.921
but not the origins of time,
right?

00:51.964 --> 00:54.576
Now, to some, that is the
Hartle-Hawking state, right,

00:54.619 --> 00:56.578
the big bang in an hourglass?

00:56.621 --> 00:58.580
Okay, yes, but...

00:58.623 --> 01:02.018
if everything that we see
and don't see...

01:02.062 --> 01:06.762
if the entire universe was once
the size of a grain of sand,

01:06.805 --> 01:07.850
smaller...

01:07.893 --> 01:09.765
- Why aren't you up there?

01:09.808 --> 01:12.072
- Elliot's the showman.

01:12.115 --> 01:13.725
- What does that make you?

01:13.769 --> 01:15.118
- The scientist.

01:15.162 --> 01:17.599
- A lot of work
and way too many drugs,

01:17.642 --> 01:19.470
I'll be honest with you,
too many joints rolled

01:19.514 --> 01:22.343
in the pages
of Asimov and H.G. Wells.

01:22.386 --> 01:25.128
- I never had a family
until Elliot

01:25.172 --> 01:28.000
invited me into this one.

01:28.044 --> 01:31.439
Hey, you leave home,
devote your life to something...

01:31.482 --> 01:33.093
you know,
people you share that with,

01:33.136 --> 01:34.703
love 'em or hate 'em
they're yours, right?

01:34.746 --> 01:36.966
- What if, in that moment,
every moment...

01:37.009 --> 01:40.970
past, present, future...
all existed at the same time?

01:41.013 --> 01:44.147
Where's my better half?
Kat, come on up here.

01:44.191 --> 01:46.149
All right, no Kat.

01:46.193 --> 01:49.021
- Oh, come on.
- Excuse me.

01:49.065 --> 01:50.719
- Thank you, Emma.

01:50.762 --> 01:52.242
Perfect.

01:54.375 --> 01:56.986
[dramatic music]

01:57.029 --> 02:01.382
A single seed...
all potential, all possibility.

02:01.425 --> 02:04.602
There's a whole life here,
and it's just waiting.

02:04.646 --> 02:07.866
It's waiting for water,
and it's waiting for sunlight.

02:07.910 --> 02:10.434
It's waiting for time.

02:11.566 --> 02:14.046
Let's give it
everything at once.

02:14.090 --> 02:20.705
♪♪

02:21.271 --> 02:24.231
[machine whirring]

02:24.274 --> 02:31.542
♪♪

02:33.370 --> 02:36.199
[alarm beeping]

02:36.243 --> 02:39.594
[ominous music]

02:39.637 --> 02:41.770
- Turn it off!
Turn it off!

02:41.813 --> 02:48.864
♪♪

02:50.735 --> 02:55.218
- Now as I face the end,
alone,

02:55.262 --> 02:57.394
with no legacy in sight,

02:57.438 --> 03:01.746
the clearer I see
the beginning.

03:04.009 --> 03:06.969
[dramatic music]

03:07.012 --> 03:14.237
♪♪

03:19.808 --> 03:21.157
Blackleaf.

03:21.201 --> 03:23.203
That's in Montana.

03:23.246 --> 03:25.422
May 11, 1852.

03:25.466 --> 03:27.250
The vagary of this
is maddening.

03:27.294 --> 03:29.165
- "The serpent eats its tail."

03:29.209 --> 03:32.386
Ouroboros.
Even the word is a mouthful.

03:32.429 --> 03:34.257
It's all I saw in my head.

03:34.301 --> 03:35.258
- Saw?

03:35.302 --> 03:36.564
- See.
See, saw.

03:36.607 --> 03:37.869
Either way, it's a message.

03:37.913 --> 03:40.263
"Dear Us.
Sincerely, the Primaries."

03:40.307 --> 03:42.570
And then "Dear Us" again.

03:42.613 --> 03:44.398
'Cause it's...
- To what end?

03:44.441 --> 03:46.704
- Loops? Cycles?
We're stuck in them.

03:46.748 --> 03:50.752
We set out to solve a problem
and end up creating one.

03:50.795 --> 03:53.407
- Maybe the Seers have a plan
to get us out of all this.

03:53.450 --> 03:56.627
- Not with a legend
or with a fairy tale.

03:56.671 --> 03:59.587
Where did you hear that again?

03:59.630 --> 04:01.241
- Something I heard as a kid.

04:01.284 --> 04:02.633
- I interned in pediatrics,

04:02.677 --> 04:05.419
heard a lot of children's
stories, but...

04:05.462 --> 04:07.116
never that one.

04:07.159 --> 04:09.597
- "There once was a serpent

04:09.640 --> 04:11.468
"that only traveled
in one direction...

04:11.512 --> 04:14.558
"always forward,
never backward...

04:14.602 --> 04:19.128
until one day,
it encountered a demon."

04:19.171 --> 04:21.652
- It's a story about time.

04:24.176 --> 04:26.744
The serpent is time.

04:29.181 --> 04:32.489
The demon, Olivia.

04:32.533 --> 04:35.100
Devouring its tail,
the endless loops.

04:36.754 --> 04:37.842
It's insanity.

04:37.886 --> 04:39.714
- The Red Forest.

04:39.757 --> 04:41.672
- The Seers are Primaries.

04:41.716 --> 04:43.283
So that means
if the story's true,

04:43.326 --> 04:45.023
they have a weapon
to fix all this,

04:45.067 --> 04:46.634
break the cycles.

04:46.677 --> 04:49.158
We need to go back
to 1852 to get it.

04:49.201 --> 04:51.029
- Uh, pioneer town?

04:51.073 --> 04:52.204
Death by dysentery?

04:52.248 --> 04:54.119
That's a wagon train of nopes.

04:54.163 --> 04:57.035
- This message, this clue...

04:57.079 --> 05:00.517
so elaborately constructed,
so carefully delivered...

05:00.561 --> 05:02.998
may represent hope,
Ms. Goines.

05:03.041 --> 05:07.524
And your ability to see time
in ways we cannot

05:07.568 --> 05:09.526
makes you our guide now.

05:11.049 --> 05:13.487
This is our last chance.

05:13.530 --> 05:17.839
[dramatic music]

05:17.882 --> 05:19.754
[gun clicking]

05:26.021 --> 05:30.155
- It was a bedtime story
my dad used to tell me.

05:30.199 --> 05:33.376
Written by my mother.

05:33.420 --> 05:36.379
- Cole...

05:36.423 --> 05:38.120
- I didn't know her.

05:38.163 --> 05:42.124
Maybe she was just some woman
who came and went, but...

05:42.167 --> 05:44.779
nothing is nothing
in all this; I know that.

05:44.822 --> 05:46.824
- She could be everything.

05:46.868 --> 05:49.218
We have to tell the others.
If Jones...

05:49.261 --> 05:51.351
- No.

05:51.394 --> 05:54.876
No, this can't be the mission.
I can't point another gun.

05:56.007 --> 06:00.055
Some things, you wanna
hold on to, you know?

06:00.098 --> 06:02.666
Even if it's just...

06:02.710 --> 06:05.147
an image in your head
of someone you never knew.

06:05.190 --> 06:08.150
[gentle music]

06:08.193 --> 06:10.892
♪♪

06:10.935 --> 06:12.589
- You're afraid that
if we ask the question,

06:12.633 --> 06:15.287
we'll have created
the answer.

06:15.331 --> 06:17.899
- Who knows
what we might find,

06:17.942 --> 06:20.815
what it'll do
to all of us again?

06:20.858 --> 06:24.035
If the Primaries meant for me
to finish this,

06:24.079 --> 06:25.689
I will.

06:25.733 --> 06:27.865
But I can't circle around,

06:27.909 --> 06:29.824
watch everyone
turn on each other

06:29.867 --> 06:32.914
while we chase the start
of this thing all over again.

06:32.957 --> 06:36.047
♪♪

06:36.091 --> 06:36.831
[keyboard clacking]

06:36.874 --> 06:40.878
[electricity crackling]

06:40.922 --> 06:41.923
[bang]

06:41.966 --> 06:44.404
[machine hums]

06:44.447 --> 06:47.494
[keyboard clacking]

06:47.537 --> 06:50.975
- I'm sending you all
to Montana 1852,

06:51.019 --> 06:52.847
the period where pioneers
found hope

06:52.890 --> 06:55.371
and expedient demise
in the New World.

06:55.415 --> 06:56.807
Make no mistake,

06:56.851 --> 07:00.463
this wilderness is as wild
as the animals within it...

07:00.507 --> 07:04.162
ravenous and untamed.

07:04.206 --> 07:07.383
[machine whirring]

07:07.427 --> 07:10.386
[sweeping music]

07:10.430 --> 07:17.654
♪♪

07:34.366 --> 07:38.632
[insects buzzing, birds cawing]

07:38.675 --> 07:40.155
- [whistles]

07:40.198 --> 07:42.505
Hold up!

07:42.549 --> 07:44.289
Who's that there?

07:44.333 --> 07:45.595
You four.

07:45.639 --> 07:48.729
- Uh, we, uh...
we came in off the road.

07:48.772 --> 07:51.383
About a half a day's walk
down that way.

07:51.427 --> 07:53.298
- You keep your hands
where I can see 'em, boy.

07:53.342 --> 07:55.213
[tense music]

07:55.257 --> 07:59.479
There ain't a damn thing
any which way for weeks.

07:59.522 --> 08:03.178
What the hell
kind of rags are those?

08:03.221 --> 08:04.919
- We saw fires up that way.

08:04.962 --> 08:07.095
We thought maybe there was
a town or something.

08:07.138 --> 08:08.662
- Me and my friend here
have been tasked

08:08.705 --> 08:10.577
with security services
for that town.

08:10.620 --> 08:12.317
"Against what?" we asked,

08:12.361 --> 08:14.537
seein' as how there ain't
no railroad, no horse ranch,

08:14.581 --> 08:16.191
not a thousand miles
from here,

08:16.234 --> 08:17.801
but there you stand.

08:17.845 --> 08:19.760
And I'll be damned if I ain't
feelin' a sight insecure.

08:19.803 --> 08:22.066
- Hey, whoa, whoa.
We're not looking for trouble.

08:22.110 --> 08:23.546
I'm just trying to see
these little ladies

08:23.590 --> 08:25.374
safely through the badlands.

08:25.417 --> 08:27.245
[gunshots]

08:27.289 --> 08:28.246
[horse whinnies]

08:28.290 --> 08:29.291
- [grunts]

08:29.334 --> 08:32.424
♪♪

08:32.467 --> 08:34.078
- Thanks, little ladies.

08:34.121 --> 08:37.081
[dramatic music]

08:37.125 --> 08:44.174
♪♪

08:51.095 --> 08:52.096
Here we go.

08:52.140 --> 08:55.317
[majestic orchestral music]

08:55.360 --> 09:02.585
♪♪

09:18.209 --> 09:19.733
- Yah!

09:19.776 --> 09:21.430
Yah! Let's go!

09:21.473 --> 09:24.433
[indistinct chatter]

09:24.476 --> 09:27.436
[foreboding music]

09:27.479 --> 09:33.877
♪♪

09:43.408 --> 09:46.629
[metallic clanking]

09:47.717 --> 09:49.458
- Keep your heads down.

09:49.501 --> 09:51.460
There aren't settlers.
They're scavs.

09:51.503 --> 09:52.766
They know their own.

09:52.809 --> 09:54.942
- Yeah, you two blend in.

09:54.985 --> 09:56.378
You...

09:56.421 --> 09:58.293
- Don't.
Hey, yes, I know.

09:58.336 --> 10:00.425
Calamity Jane
and Mad Maxine here

10:00.469 --> 10:02.471
took all the good wardrobe.

10:02.514 --> 10:05.300
You guys,
I need a costume.

10:05.343 --> 10:08.303
[sly music]

10:08.346 --> 10:15.136
♪♪

10:15.179 --> 10:17.834
- [with Southern accent]
Well, howdy there, little lady.

10:17.878 --> 10:19.314
You mind iffen I...
[fence creaks]

10:19.357 --> 10:20.402
[clears throat]

10:20.445 --> 10:22.665
Jaw with you for a moment?

10:24.493 --> 10:28.889
Well,
me and my posse,

10:28.932 --> 10:31.674
we was down
by the waterin' hole.

10:31.718 --> 10:34.372
By gum, we were
set upon by bandits.

10:34.416 --> 10:37.637
And those bandits,
they robbed us up, down,

10:37.680 --> 10:40.030
and in between
and sideways, and...

10:40.074 --> 10:43.512
[loudly] they sure
took their time doing it.

10:43.555 --> 10:46.123
[normal volume] Yeah, they, uh,
robbed us so bad,

10:46.167 --> 10:48.691
we was fixin'
to call the law,

10:48.735 --> 10:50.954
give 'em some six-gun justice.

10:53.478 --> 10:55.698
[normal voice] Okay, good talk.
See you later.

11:01.138 --> 11:04.315
[Oingo Boingo's "Weird Science"
playing on piano]

11:04.359 --> 11:11.409
♪♪

11:12.672 --> 11:15.109
[doors creak, thud]

11:15.152 --> 11:19.026
♪♪

11:19.069 --> 11:20.810
- Four whiskey sours.

11:20.854 --> 11:23.726
- My whiskey ain't sour.

11:25.032 --> 11:28.339
- Bottle and four glasses.
Pick your shelf.

11:28.383 --> 11:35.433
♪♪

11:38.915 --> 11:41.744
Something is very off
about this place.

11:41.788 --> 11:44.399
- Yeah, you're right.

11:44.442 --> 11:45.705
Hey.
[snaps fingers]

11:45.748 --> 11:47.532
Princess Primary,
you see anything yet?

11:47.576 --> 11:49.056
What's taking so long?

11:49.099 --> 11:50.884
- Stop obsessing
about what I'm seeing

11:50.927 --> 11:53.669
and start asking yourself
what you're not.

11:53.713 --> 11:56.541
Whiskey, neat, from 1972.

11:56.585 --> 11:59.196
Black hat over there
with the nine-millimeter Glock?

11:59.240 --> 12:01.242
That's nine shots more
than a six-shooter.

12:01.285 --> 12:04.332
And table two over there
with the military tac boots?

12:04.375 --> 12:06.421
And that chucklehead's
got an iWatch.

12:06.464 --> 12:07.683
And open your ears.

12:07.727 --> 12:10.251
The piano player?
Oingo Boingo?

12:10.294 --> 12:12.122
"Weird Science."

12:12.166 --> 12:15.430
That tune's, like,
130 years too early.

12:15.473 --> 12:18.433
[foreboding music]

12:18.476 --> 12:22.089
♪♪

12:22.132 --> 12:24.047
- Hannah, what is it?

12:24.091 --> 12:28.443
- That man is Elliot Jones.

12:28.486 --> 12:30.097
My father.

12:34.318 --> 12:36.930
["The Munsters" theme song
playing on piano]

12:36.973 --> 12:41.108
♪♪

12:41.151 --> 12:43.719
- He's playing "The Munsters."

12:43.763 --> 12:47.331
♪♪

12:47.375 --> 12:50.900
- What's your father doing
here in the past?

12:50.944 --> 12:53.598
♪♪

12:53.642 --> 12:54.686
- Mr. Jones.

12:54.730 --> 12:56.384
♪♪

12:56.427 --> 12:58.473
- Aw, come on, man.

12:58.516 --> 13:01.041
You know, there's your time,
there's our time,

13:01.084 --> 13:03.130
and then there's my time.

13:03.173 --> 13:05.219
This is supposed to be my time.

13:05.262 --> 13:06.786
- You can play your music later.

13:06.829 --> 13:08.265
Your employer
would like to see you.

13:08.309 --> 13:10.050
[thunder rumbling faintly]

13:10.093 --> 13:12.400
[piano music resumes]

13:12.443 --> 13:14.837
[piano lid bangs]
- God damn it!

13:14.881 --> 13:16.883
You are inhospitable.

13:16.926 --> 13:18.536
All right, all right.

13:18.580 --> 13:20.408
Let's not keep the man waiting.

13:22.149 --> 13:24.238
[ominous music]

13:24.281 --> 13:27.502
[thunder rumbling]

13:29.156 --> 13:31.985
[doors creaking]

13:32.028 --> 13:37.207
♪♪

13:37.251 --> 13:38.992
Mr. Shaw.

13:40.950 --> 13:42.169
- Who is that?

13:42.212 --> 13:43.387
- Thought we had
that conversation...

13:43.431 --> 13:45.433
- The Tall Man.

13:45.476 --> 13:48.001
- I thought you said
Olivia killed him.

13:48.044 --> 13:50.568
- Well, clearly,
this is before that, isn't it?

13:50.612 --> 13:51.918
- "Sir" suits me just fine.

13:51.961 --> 13:55.095
Additional requests
for modification.

13:55.138 --> 13:56.618
Here.

13:56.661 --> 13:58.054
It's from the home office.

13:58.098 --> 13:59.403
- Ah.

14:00.709 --> 14:02.798
Why the hell do you need
this much power?

14:02.842 --> 14:03.930
- Insurance.

14:03.973 --> 14:08.238
[thunder rumbling]

14:08.282 --> 14:10.371
- What's in those wagons?

14:10.414 --> 14:12.939
- Whoa, uh,
so this is the sort of thing

14:12.982 --> 14:16.551
that we... we normally
insure against.

14:16.594 --> 14:17.813
- Yeah, your work...

14:17.857 --> 14:19.206
your important work,
your legacy...

14:19.249 --> 14:21.817
- Uh-huh.
- It's almost finished.

14:21.861 --> 14:23.863
We need you to implement
these modifications,

14:23.906 --> 14:26.735
lest it not be you
who completes it.

14:26.778 --> 14:29.520
- I'm on it.
- Good.

14:29.564 --> 14:31.914
In the morning.

14:31.958 --> 14:35.831
[whistling]

14:35.875 --> 14:37.180
- Move it out.

14:37.224 --> 14:38.965
Get 'em there by morning.

14:39.008 --> 14:42.316
[tense music]

14:42.359 --> 14:44.971
- My father...

14:45.014 --> 14:46.929
he's working with them.

14:46.973 --> 14:49.279
♪♪

14:49.323 --> 14:50.846
- Let's find out why.

14:50.890 --> 14:53.980
["Knight Rider" theme
playing on piano]

14:54.023 --> 14:57.461
♪♪

14:57.505 --> 14:59.594
- All right, you varmints,

14:59.637 --> 15:01.422
reach for the sky!

15:01.465 --> 15:03.685
[gunshots]

15:03.728 --> 15:04.816
You!

15:04.860 --> 15:07.907
Play something
you can dance to.

15:07.950 --> 15:09.169
[piano gongs]

15:09.212 --> 15:10.953
[gunshots]

15:10.997 --> 15:15.001
[impish music]

15:15.044 --> 15:18.439
Next time a man asks for
a whiskey sour in this town,

15:18.482 --> 15:20.963
you better have it ready!

15:21.007 --> 15:22.965
- Ow!

15:23.009 --> 15:24.271
What the...

15:24.314 --> 15:25.402
[whooshes]

15:25.446 --> 15:27.056
[horse neighs]
[gunshots]

15:27.100 --> 15:28.536
- Whoo!
[laughs]

15:28.579 --> 15:30.581
Adios, amigos!

15:31.582 --> 15:34.585
[machine whirring]

15:38.589 --> 15:41.897
[tense music]

15:41.941 --> 15:42.942
- Raritan...

15:42.985 --> 15:46.032
♪♪

15:46.075 --> 15:49.209
- Elliot.

15:49.252 --> 15:50.645
- Kat?

15:51.254 --> 15:55.780
[machine whirring]

15:57.913 --> 15:59.219
Whoa.

15:59.262 --> 16:01.395
Okay.

16:01.438 --> 16:03.614
Okay, what the hell is this?

16:03.658 --> 16:06.617
♪♪

16:06.661 --> 16:09.838
[eagle cries]

16:13.624 --> 16:16.497
- We've been tracking
these wagons for hours.

16:16.540 --> 16:18.194
- We're not stopping.

16:18.238 --> 16:20.588
- You're not supposed
to be here.

16:20.631 --> 16:22.024
Christ, Kat,
when the hell is this?

16:22.068 --> 16:23.721
You're so much...

16:23.765 --> 16:25.767
- "Wiser" is the word
I hope you're searching for.

16:25.810 --> 16:27.595
- Yeah.
- There was a town.

16:27.638 --> 16:28.944
He was with them.

16:28.988 --> 16:30.990
The Army of the 12 Monkeys.

16:31.033 --> 16:35.951
♪♪

16:35.995 --> 16:39.824
- Elliot,
what are you doing in the past?

16:39.868 --> 16:41.087
- You don't understand.

16:41.130 --> 16:43.698
I spent the last
ten years building.

16:43.741 --> 16:46.614
Building something monumental.

16:46.657 --> 16:48.964
A research vessel.

16:49.008 --> 16:51.836
An ark that can
travel through time.

16:53.186 --> 16:55.840
- Elliot, dear God,

16:55.884 --> 16:57.668
don't tell me you...

16:57.712 --> 17:01.672
♪♪

17:01.716 --> 17:03.892
- It's called Titan.

17:09.070 --> 17:10.071
- [grunts]

17:10.116 --> 17:11.073
- That's enough, Hannah.

17:11.117 --> 17:12.422
- We should lock him up now

17:12.465 --> 17:14.076
and decide how best
to interrogate.

17:14.119 --> 17:16.731
- That won't be necessary.

17:16.773 --> 17:18.776
- He built Titan.

17:18.819 --> 17:21.214
They didn't take his work.
He gave it to them.

17:21.257 --> 17:23.477
- [sighs]
- How can you be so calm?

17:23.520 --> 17:26.871
Why aren't you ready to kill him
right here and now?

17:26.915 --> 17:28.917
- There are few people

17:28.960 --> 17:30.397
whose death
you consider more

17:30.440 --> 17:32.660
than the one you marry,
I assure you.

17:32.703 --> 17:33.965
- But, Mother...

17:34.009 --> 17:35.054
- If you think
I'm being merciful,

17:35.097 --> 17:36.272
there are worse weapons.

17:36.316 --> 17:40.102
Knives that cut deeper, slower,

17:40.146 --> 17:43.149
more painfully.

17:43.192 --> 17:44.367
- What is all this?

17:44.411 --> 17:46.587
- Welcome to the future,
Elliot.

17:46.630 --> 17:48.284
It's history.

17:49.894 --> 17:51.853
- Is this...
- Yup.

17:51.896 --> 17:53.115
- All right,
I want some goddamn answers,

17:53.159 --> 17:54.377
and I want them now.

17:54.421 --> 17:57.902
What the hell happened
to... everything?

17:57.946 --> 17:59.252
The past, the future,
this place?

17:59.295 --> 18:00.688
What have you done
with my machine?

18:00.731 --> 18:02.255
- Don't you dare.
- What are you doing here?

18:02.298 --> 18:04.126
And who the hell is she?

18:05.301 --> 18:06.911
- Hannah, if you wouldn't mind,

18:06.955 --> 18:10.698
I'd appreciate a moment alone
with your father.

18:10.741 --> 18:13.701
[dramatic music]

18:13.744 --> 18:15.006
♪♪

18:15.050 --> 18:17.618
- It's baby Titan.

18:17.661 --> 18:19.272
- Look what it's done
to the land,

18:19.315 --> 18:20.882
the trees.
- Makes sense.

18:20.925 --> 18:22.927
Where else would you build
a time-traveling city

18:22.971 --> 18:24.799
but in the past?

18:24.842 --> 18:26.105
- Why not in the future?

18:26.148 --> 18:28.150
- No labor.
Everyone's dead.

18:28.194 --> 18:31.414
Here, workers can disappear
without question.

18:31.458 --> 18:33.982
- Let's get a closer look.

18:34.025 --> 18:36.376
- Uh...

18:36.419 --> 18:39.596
[slow suspenseful music]

18:39.640 --> 18:41.163
♪♪

18:41.207 --> 18:44.993
- Hey, the wagons.

18:45.036 --> 18:46.821
- That's a Jonesy core.

18:46.864 --> 18:54.133
♪♪

18:56.135 --> 18:57.875
- Technology's brought in
from the future.

18:57.919 --> 19:00.443
Framework's built here
in the past.

19:00.487 --> 19:02.924
- Why would the Primaries
bring us here?

19:02.967 --> 19:05.927
Why now?

19:05.970 --> 19:07.407
- I don't know.

19:07.450 --> 19:09.844
Iceberg Titan
before it goes all Titanic?

19:09.887 --> 19:12.847
I mean, even I can see that.

19:12.890 --> 19:14.892
- What do you mean, even you?

19:14.936 --> 19:16.242
- Whoa!

19:16.285 --> 19:17.852
Got three of our boys facedown

19:17.895 --> 19:19.506
in the woods outside of town.

19:19.549 --> 19:22.030
We got an outsider!
Lock it down!

19:22.073 --> 19:23.118
Over there!

19:23.162 --> 19:26.817
[suspenseful music]

19:26.861 --> 19:28.863
[gunshots]
- [yelps]

19:28.906 --> 19:30.299
♪♪

19:30.343 --> 19:33.041
[gunshots]
[gasps]

19:33.084 --> 19:40.048
♪♪

19:40.091 --> 19:43.269
[yelping]

19:44.922 --> 19:52.147
♪♪

19:53.627 --> 19:55.716
[guns clicking]

19:55.759 --> 20:02.766
♪♪

20:03.550 --> 20:05.160
- [gurgles]

20:05.204 --> 20:08.337
♪♪

20:08.381 --> 20:11.558
- Whoa, bro,
she just really saved your ass.

20:11.601 --> 20:13.603
[gun cocks]
- Let's go.

20:13.647 --> 20:15.910
♪♪

20:15.953 --> 20:17.607
- I didn't know.

20:17.651 --> 20:20.871
I couldn't possibly
know about this.

20:20.915 --> 20:22.221
Or her.

20:22.264 --> 20:24.353
- Start with this.

20:24.397 --> 20:26.225
- They were funding
my research for years.

20:26.268 --> 20:29.663
They... they said it was
insurance.

20:29.706 --> 20:31.099
Saving the future.

20:31.142 --> 20:33.841
- They played to your ego,
Elliot.

20:33.884 --> 20:35.190
It's a very simple instrument.

20:35.234 --> 20:37.323
- It was meant
to outsource discovery...

20:37.366 --> 20:39.629
not change history,
just use it better.

20:39.673 --> 20:42.197
I mean,
you want a cure for cancer?

20:42.241 --> 20:44.155
Give me a hundred years.
I'll be back tomorrow.

20:44.199 --> 20:47.158
- You are no savior.

20:47.202 --> 20:51.119
You're Oppenheimer
in a blindfold.

20:51.162 --> 20:53.426
- And you're a mother.

20:53.469 --> 20:55.079
So I guess
we both became something

20:55.123 --> 20:56.472
we never wanted to be.

20:59.519 --> 21:02.696
- I had a change of heart
after you left.

21:02.739 --> 21:04.393
- I didn't leave.

21:04.437 --> 21:06.352
I didn't choose this over you.

21:06.395 --> 21:08.354
You left me no choice
but you, only you.

21:08.397 --> 21:09.964
- You wanted a legacy.

21:10.007 --> 21:11.444
- I wanted a family, Kat,

21:11.487 --> 21:14.403
something we could
make together and...

21:14.447 --> 21:19.626
watch it grow and invent
itself or herself.

21:19.669 --> 21:23.151
The shakes.
What's with the shakes?

21:23.194 --> 21:25.284
- Splinter radiation.

21:25.327 --> 21:27.895
Lethal exposure
trying to escape

21:27.938 --> 21:29.940
your masterpiece.

21:32.769 --> 21:34.858
Four weeks.

21:34.902 --> 21:37.557
Six at best.

21:37.600 --> 21:39.820
Nobody knows.

21:39.863 --> 21:41.300
Especially not her.

21:44.041 --> 21:46.174
- [sighs]

21:46.217 --> 21:50.091
- I didn't know
how to be a mother.

21:50.134 --> 21:51.658
My mother never taught me.

21:51.701 --> 21:53.355
My father loved me
through postcards

21:53.399 --> 21:56.358
and birthday chocolates.

21:56.402 --> 22:00.710
I wanted to be great
at something I was good at,

22:00.754 --> 22:03.365
not afraid
of something I wasn't.

22:06.586 --> 22:09.284
- The day you told me
you were pregnant,

22:09.328 --> 22:11.373
it felt like I won
the Nobel Prize,

22:11.417 --> 22:13.375
that I'd invented the wheel.

22:14.855 --> 22:17.466
And when you told me that the
next day, you wouldn't be, I...

22:17.510 --> 22:20.513
- You stole our work
and you left.

22:20.556 --> 22:23.733
- I thought it was
the only child I had left.

22:23.777 --> 22:26.736
[gentle music]

22:26.780 --> 22:32.568
♪♪

22:32.612 --> 22:34.788
Man.

22:34.831 --> 22:36.833
Took us two decades
to invent time travel

22:36.877 --> 22:40.228
but just six days of marriage
to ruin each other.

22:40.271 --> 22:47.453
♪♪

22:48.976 --> 22:50.673
- Eff this!
[panting]

22:50.717 --> 22:52.371
- What are you doing?
We gotta keep moving.

22:52.414 --> 22:54.677
- I want out.
- There is no out.

22:54.721 --> 22:56.766
We're here for a reason.
Come on.

22:56.810 --> 22:58.899
- You know,
we're not prepared for this.

23:01.292 --> 23:03.077
- Fine, then go.

23:03.120 --> 23:04.165
- James.

23:04.208 --> 23:05.427
- You wanna leave, leave.

23:05.471 --> 23:07.298
I don't have a choice.

23:07.342 --> 23:10.389
She stays. She's Primary.

23:10.432 --> 23:13.870
- Was Primary.

23:13.914 --> 23:16.438
Not anymore.

23:16.482 --> 23:18.135
- What are you talking about?

23:18.179 --> 23:19.659
- I'm right, aren't I?

23:19.702 --> 23:22.792
- Uh, I don't know
what's happening to me.

23:22.836 --> 23:25.708
Visions and the voices...
they're, like, gone.

23:25.752 --> 23:28.145
- What the hell
are we even doing here, then?

23:28.189 --> 23:29.451
Why didn't you say something?

23:29.495 --> 23:31.192
- Because she was afraid.
- Afraid of what?

23:31.235 --> 23:33.194
- Of everyone turning on her.

23:33.237 --> 23:34.456
- I...

23:34.500 --> 23:35.979
[leaves rustling]

23:36.023 --> 23:38.982
[dramatic music]

23:39.026 --> 23:40.810
♪♪

23:40.854 --> 23:44.945
- I've been waiting for you...
Primary.

23:50.603 --> 23:50.820
.

23:50.864 --> 23:52.518
[crickets chirping]

23:52.561 --> 23:55.738
[foreboding music]

23:55.782 --> 23:58.088
♪♪

23:58.132 --> 23:59.699
- You've seen these things?

23:59.742 --> 24:02.005
- I have.

24:02.049 --> 24:03.659
But I'm not like you.

24:03.703 --> 24:05.618
- Who are you?

24:05.661 --> 24:09.360
- I am Tihkoosue
of the Siksika.

24:09.404 --> 24:11.450
- You should really
do movie trailers.

24:11.493 --> 24:14.235
♪♪

24:14.278 --> 24:16.019
- You speak English.

24:16.063 --> 24:18.369
- When my family was killed,

24:18.413 --> 24:20.197
I was raised by your kind.

24:20.241 --> 24:23.723
Later, I returned
to this land.

24:23.766 --> 24:25.855
Now...

24:25.899 --> 24:27.814
it bleeds.

24:27.857 --> 24:30.512
♪♪

24:30.556 --> 24:35.082
When I drink, I can see them.

24:35.125 --> 24:36.997
- Who?

24:37.040 --> 24:39.695
♪♪

24:39.739 --> 24:43.612
- The ones who sent you here
from long ago.

24:43.656 --> 24:45.048
- Primaries?

24:45.092 --> 24:46.963
Where/when are they?

24:47.007 --> 24:48.878
I need to talk to them.

24:48.922 --> 24:50.880
I need to see what you see.

24:50.924 --> 24:52.142
- You must not.

24:52.186 --> 24:53.492
[dramatic music]

24:53.535 --> 24:55.842
Death is there.

24:55.885 --> 24:57.974
A watcher.

24:58.018 --> 25:00.368
Looking for you.

25:00.411 --> 25:01.717
- Olivia.

25:01.761 --> 25:04.415
- The Witness must never
know of the weapon

25:04.459 --> 25:07.244
that the Seers
have made for you.

25:07.288 --> 25:10.030
- A weapon
to destroy the demon.

25:10.073 --> 25:11.945
How do we find it?

25:11.988 --> 25:14.425
- Climb the steps.

25:14.469 --> 25:16.384
Ring the bell.

25:16.427 --> 25:19.213
- Climb the steps.
Ring the bell.

25:19.256 --> 25:22.912
I-I used to hear that
all the time

25:22.956 --> 25:24.435
in my head.

25:24.479 --> 25:27.961
- What does it mean?

25:28.004 --> 25:30.572
- I don't know.

25:30.616 --> 25:33.575
- 16 people died
in this machine

25:33.619 --> 25:36.230
until one didn't.

25:36.273 --> 25:37.840
It wasn't I who made it work.

25:37.884 --> 25:39.799
It was James Cole.

25:39.842 --> 25:42.323
- Well, it's a far cry
from day one here.

25:42.366 --> 25:44.630
Remember that?

25:44.673 --> 25:46.632
- You were quite the performer.

25:46.675 --> 25:50.244
Seeking my attention,
receiving hers.

25:50.287 --> 25:51.985
What was her name?

25:52.028 --> 25:54.857
Your assistant?

25:54.901 --> 25:56.119
- Emma?

25:56.163 --> 25:57.425
She's just a kid.

25:57.468 --> 26:00.384
- Yeah, but you always
had eyes for her.

26:00.428 --> 26:03.779
She was brilliant.

26:03.823 --> 26:05.085
And beautiful.

26:05.128 --> 26:07.435
- I already had one of those.

26:09.742 --> 26:13.397
I admit,
it was not my finest hour.

26:13.441 --> 26:16.618
Eventually,
everything caught fire.

26:16.662 --> 26:18.751
In the end, we scrapped
the program for Splinter

26:18.794 --> 26:21.536
'cause there was never
enough power to make it...

26:21.580 --> 26:23.277
make it run properly.

26:23.320 --> 26:26.715
♪♪

26:26.759 --> 26:29.326
There was never enough power.

26:29.370 --> 26:31.633
- What is it?

26:31.677 --> 26:33.374
- Space without time,

26:33.417 --> 26:35.158
it's a where without a when.

26:35.202 --> 26:36.595
It's the Hartle-Hawking state.

26:36.638 --> 26:37.813
Kat, they're not building Titan

26:37.857 --> 26:39.554
so that they can
travel across time.

26:39.598 --> 26:41.991
They wanna punch a hole
right through the middle of it.

26:42.035 --> 26:44.864
Titan can create a paradox
that is big enough to...

26:44.907 --> 26:48.824
- To melt away the structure
of time and space.

26:48.868 --> 26:50.304
- Yeah.

26:50.347 --> 26:52.828
- The Red Forest.

26:52.872 --> 26:55.875
♪♪

26:55.918 --> 26:56.919
- [sighs]

26:56.963 --> 26:58.442
We're dead in the water.

26:58.486 --> 27:01.315
If Jennifer can't see anything,
we got nowhere to go.

27:01.358 --> 27:04.013
[dramatic music]

27:04.057 --> 27:06.320
- Hey!
What are you doing?

27:06.363 --> 27:08.496
- I have to see.
I have to see!

27:08.539 --> 27:10.150
- It's too dangerous.

27:10.193 --> 27:12.282
- [gasping]

27:12.326 --> 27:14.241
- Jennifer?

27:14.284 --> 27:16.417
Jennifer!

27:16.460 --> 27:18.332
- "Always forward,
never backward."

27:18.375 --> 27:19.463
- "They created a weapon."

27:19.507 --> 27:22.553
- "The serpent was doomed."

27:22.597 --> 27:24.381
- Primaries.

27:24.425 --> 27:28.603
♪♪

27:28.647 --> 27:30.910
- Oh, you fool.

27:30.953 --> 27:32.868
She will hear.

27:32.912 --> 27:33.956
She will see.

27:34.000 --> 27:36.350
You will lead her
straight to us.

27:36.393 --> 27:39.135
- Tell me how to find
the weapon.

27:39.179 --> 27:41.050
- Climb the steps.

27:41.094 --> 27:43.052
Ring the bell.

27:43.096 --> 27:45.272
[whirring]

27:45.315 --> 27:46.490
- Weapon?

27:46.534 --> 27:48.231
What weapon?

27:48.275 --> 27:53.584
♪♪

27:53.628 --> 27:56.065
- [grunts]

27:59.068 --> 28:00.766
When is this moment?

28:01.984 --> 28:03.333
Where?

28:03.377 --> 28:04.595
- Ring the bell!

28:04.639 --> 28:09.122
[distorted whispers]

28:09.165 --> 28:12.125
[ominous music]

28:12.168 --> 28:19.219
♪♪

28:19.785 --> 28:23.919
- [distorted voice]
James.

28:23.963 --> 28:26.139
Dr. Railly.

28:26.182 --> 28:29.011
1852.

28:29.055 --> 28:30.404
[slap]
Ow!

28:30.447 --> 28:32.101
- [inhales sharply]

28:32.145 --> 28:34.190
- [gasps]

28:35.670 --> 28:38.107
She knows now.

28:38.151 --> 28:40.283
About the weapon.

28:40.327 --> 28:41.545
About everything.

28:41.589 --> 28:47.290
♪♪

28:47.334 --> 28:48.944
- Oh, I hate needles.

28:48.988 --> 28:49.771
[whimpers]

28:49.815 --> 28:51.773
- What are you doing?

28:51.817 --> 28:53.122
- Elliot's going back.

28:53.166 --> 28:54.776
I've got a lock
on Mr. Cole's tether.

28:54.820 --> 28:57.387
It's faint, but I can
get you to their position.

28:57.431 --> 28:58.954
- I'm going with him.

28:58.998 --> 29:00.651
And don't even for a moment
suggest that I don't.

29:00.695 --> 29:03.480
- Definitely yours.

29:03.524 --> 29:05.482
- Ours.

29:05.526 --> 29:12.751
♪♪

29:18.191 --> 29:19.453
- [exhales]

29:19.496 --> 29:21.455
Kat?

29:21.498 --> 29:23.849
I loved you, you know.

29:23.892 --> 29:25.198
I did.

29:25.241 --> 29:27.069
In my way.

29:27.113 --> 29:29.289
[machine whirring]

29:29.332 --> 29:31.639
- I suppose

29:31.682 --> 29:33.119
I in mine.

29:38.428 --> 29:39.778
- All right.

29:39.821 --> 29:41.170
[stammering]
What did we used to say? Uh...

29:41.214 --> 29:42.302
- Initiate...

29:42.345 --> 29:43.520
both:
Splinter sequence.

29:43.564 --> 29:46.785
[whooshing]

29:49.178 --> 29:50.832
[whooshing]

29:50.876 --> 29:52.791
- The 12 Monkeys
want to use Titan

29:52.834 --> 29:54.575
to create the Red Forest.

29:54.618 --> 29:56.838
- Whatever happened
to paradoxing Primaries?

29:56.882 --> 29:58.361
- If you wanna destroy time,
you need to create

29:58.405 --> 30:01.234
a paradox so big that
it can't be undone, right?

30:01.277 --> 30:02.844
You need a-a nuclear option.

30:02.888 --> 30:04.541
- So what do we do?
- Okay, well, Titan was built

30:04.585 --> 30:06.195
in pieces and places
all across time.

30:06.239 --> 30:08.937
It was meant to be assembled
all at once in a single moment.

30:08.981 --> 30:10.678
- Rome in a day.
- Exactly.

30:10.721 --> 30:13.420
And that out there
is the main tower.

30:13.463 --> 30:14.551
That's the control center.

30:14.595 --> 30:15.683
That's where they wanna focus

30:15.726 --> 30:17.467
all these power upgrades.

30:17.511 --> 30:20.209
Now, there should be a bunch
of wagons full of power cores.

30:20.253 --> 30:21.558
- Six of them. Maybe more.

30:21.602 --> 30:22.864
- Okay.
- What do you wanna do?

30:22.908 --> 30:24.735
- Oh, blow them the hell up,
man.

30:24.779 --> 30:26.825
We can't stop Titan, but...

30:26.868 --> 30:28.261
maybe we can keep them
from weaponizing it.

30:28.304 --> 30:31.090
- We're a hundred years away
from grenades or C4.

30:31.133 --> 30:33.266
Where are we gonna...
- No, dynamite, man.

30:33.309 --> 30:34.920
We got crates of the shit.

30:34.963 --> 30:38.271
They keep it at the far end
of the site for mining.

30:38.314 --> 30:40.055
Now, they're gonna
be looking for me.

30:40.099 --> 30:42.884
So I will go pay my respects
to the Tall Man

30:42.928 --> 30:44.886
and keep him distracted,
you know, and...

30:44.930 --> 30:46.105
- Howdy!

30:46.148 --> 30:48.672
- You guys do your
Team Splinter thing.

30:48.716 --> 30:51.675
[adventurous music]

30:51.719 --> 30:58.944
♪♪

31:05.951 --> 31:08.344
You know, you look
just like my sister.

31:08.388 --> 31:11.739
You got my mother's nose
and my father's eyes.

31:13.175 --> 31:15.221
Can only imagine
what you think of me.

31:15.264 --> 31:16.787
- I don't.

31:16.831 --> 31:19.616
I never thought of my father.

31:19.660 --> 31:21.270
I never had a reason to.

31:21.314 --> 31:24.708
- Let's see if I can make
a lasting impression.

31:24.752 --> 31:31.977
♪♪

31:46.426 --> 31:48.036
Okay, this is me.

31:48.080 --> 31:49.472
Uh...

31:49.516 --> 31:50.647
[exhales sharply]

31:50.691 --> 31:51.953
When everything goes wrong

31:51.997 --> 31:53.302
and the whole world
goes to shit,

31:53.346 --> 31:56.044
don't be here for that, okay?
Please?

31:56.088 --> 31:59.265
This is nothing if not for you.

31:59.308 --> 32:05.053
♪♪

32:05.097 --> 32:08.317
Whoo, it's a hot one
out there today.

32:08.361 --> 32:09.623
- Where have you been?

32:09.666 --> 32:10.841
- [sighs]

32:10.885 --> 32:12.147
Hell of a night, man.

32:12.191 --> 32:13.757
Hell of a night,
I tell you what.

32:13.801 --> 32:14.845
[glass clinks]

32:14.889 --> 32:16.238
You got family, Shaw?

32:16.282 --> 32:19.720
- Oh, I lost both my parents
as a young child.

32:19.763 --> 32:22.288
Tragically for them,
at least.

32:22.331 --> 32:24.507
Formatively for me.

32:24.551 --> 32:26.422
- Kids?
- No.

32:26.466 --> 32:29.382
- Well, turns out,
my pallid friend,

32:29.425 --> 32:35.344
that I, much to my utter
and "holy shit" surprise,

32:35.388 --> 32:37.172
am a father.

32:38.565 --> 32:39.958
Mm-hmm.

32:40.001 --> 32:41.872
And although I'm still
what you might call

32:41.916 --> 32:44.527
processing it... you know,
denial, acceptance,

32:44.571 --> 32:46.703
picking out colors for a room
I never got to paint...

32:46.747 --> 32:48.705
I have learned something.

32:48.749 --> 32:51.621
There's this thing
every father...

32:51.665 --> 32:53.580
every good father...

32:53.623 --> 32:55.930
would do for their kid.

32:55.974 --> 32:57.410
Wanna know what it is?

33:00.543 --> 33:03.633
[ominous music]

33:03.677 --> 33:05.113
- Tell me, Elliot.

33:05.157 --> 33:08.160
What would a father
do for their children?

33:08.203 --> 33:09.378
- Fight.

33:09.422 --> 33:12.381
[suspenseful music]

33:12.425 --> 33:19.475
♪♪

33:44.892 --> 33:48.243
[gunshots]

33:48.287 --> 33:51.246
[dramatic music]

33:51.290 --> 33:54.510
♪♪

33:54.554 --> 33:57.557
[faint gunfire]

33:57.600 --> 34:04.085
♪♪

34:04.129 --> 34:06.218
[gunfire continues]

34:06.261 --> 34:08.089
- I don't understand.
Why would he go after us?

34:08.132 --> 34:10.657
- Best guess,
we left him to die.

34:10.699 --> 34:12.614
[gunfire]

34:12.659 --> 34:14.704
But you're welcome to ask.

34:14.748 --> 34:21.275
♪♪

34:21.320 --> 34:23.452
- I come with word
from the home office.

34:23.496 --> 34:25.628
You're done here. Compromised.

34:25.672 --> 34:26.976
Get Titan to another time.

34:27.021 --> 34:30.806
[men yelling, gunfire]

34:30.851 --> 34:33.810
The Witness has spoken.

34:33.853 --> 34:35.377
- We need the architect.

34:35.420 --> 34:38.076
Titan cannot
be completed without him.

34:40.687 --> 34:42.949
- Clear the perimeter.

34:42.993 --> 34:46.040
Initiate splinter sequence.

34:46.649 --> 34:47.781
[gun cocks]

34:47.824 --> 34:50.175
- Where do you think
you're going?

34:52.481 --> 34:55.614
♪♪

34:55.658 --> 34:57.834
- You're really good at that.

34:57.878 --> 34:59.053
- We have to go.

34:59.097 --> 35:03.710
[machine whirring]

35:03.753 --> 35:05.015
- Titan's leaving.

35:05.059 --> 35:07.670
So should we.

35:07.714 --> 35:13.023
♪♪

35:13.067 --> 35:14.764
- We can make it back.

35:14.808 --> 35:15.765
We can still make it.

35:15.809 --> 35:17.332
[gunshot]

35:17.376 --> 35:19.682
♪♪

35:19.726 --> 35:21.380
- [gasps]

35:21.423 --> 35:22.729
- [yells]

35:22.772 --> 35:24.600
- [grunts]

35:24.644 --> 35:27.864
- [shrieking]

35:27.908 --> 35:35.133
♪♪

35:37.874 --> 35:38.832
- Deacon?

35:38.875 --> 35:40.355
[whooshing]

35:40.399 --> 35:46.535
♪♪

35:46.579 --> 35:48.885
- Father.

35:48.929 --> 35:51.888
[soft music]

35:51.932 --> 35:55.065
♪♪

35:55.109 --> 35:56.632
- [gasps]

35:56.676 --> 35:58.156
At least I got to see...

35:58.199 --> 36:00.114
♪♪

36:00.158 --> 36:03.900
The best thing I ever made.

36:03.944 --> 36:07.382
[machine whirring]

36:07.426 --> 36:13.388
♪♪

36:13.432 --> 36:16.217
[whooshing]

36:16.261 --> 36:18.611
[electricity crackling]

36:18.654 --> 36:20.743
[thunder rumbling]

36:20.787 --> 36:28.055
♪♪

36:39.153 --> 36:40.502
[alarm rings]

36:40.546 --> 36:43.810
[machine whirring]

36:50.164 --> 36:53.341
[whooshing]

36:56.649 --> 36:59.826
[soft dramatic music]

36:59.869 --> 37:06.876
♪♪

37:13.361 --> 37:16.669
- Mother, I know you're ill.

37:16.712 --> 37:19.367
I see the way your hand shakes.

37:20.716 --> 37:22.457
It is the privilege of a child

37:22.501 --> 37:26.287
to walk their parents
the rest of the way...

37:26.331 --> 37:28.333
together.

37:28.376 --> 37:33.599
♪♪

37:33.642 --> 37:35.514
What did he give us?

37:35.557 --> 37:36.863
[computer beeping]

37:36.906 --> 37:40.345
- Everything Elliot knew
about Titan.

37:40.388 --> 37:42.521
[horns blaring]

37:42.564 --> 37:44.566
- They're searching
for something.

37:46.089 --> 37:47.656
A weapon.

37:47.700 --> 37:50.442
Something built
by Primaries in the past.

37:50.485 --> 37:52.444
Crafted for them.

37:52.487 --> 37:55.316
- To use against you?

37:55.360 --> 37:56.926
We'll find it.

37:56.970 --> 37:58.754
- We will.

37:58.798 --> 38:01.235
In the meantime,
Titan must be completed

38:01.279 --> 38:04.151
so it can fulfill its purpose.

38:04.194 --> 38:06.327
- You got a plan for that?

38:06.371 --> 38:09.025
- Already in motion.

38:09.069 --> 38:11.419
Has been for some time.

38:13.595 --> 38:15.641
- Whatever Titan
may have been built for,

38:15.684 --> 38:17.904
whatever it might do,

38:17.947 --> 38:19.862
certainly,
Olivia has her weapon,

38:19.906 --> 38:22.300
and we, too, must find ours.

38:22.343 --> 38:25.303
Ms. Goines,
how do I find it?

38:25.346 --> 38:28.175
- Climb the steps.
Ring the bell.

38:28.218 --> 38:29.481
- It's another clue.

38:29.524 --> 38:31.961
- Olivia has it too now.
And she's not alone.

38:32.005 --> 38:33.615
- Mr. Deacon.

38:33.659 --> 38:35.922
- I refuse to believe...
- You better start.

38:35.965 --> 38:38.272
Deacon we saw today
is the one I've always known.

38:38.316 --> 38:39.360
He turns on a dime.

38:39.404 --> 38:41.057
- But he must have a reason.

38:41.101 --> 38:44.278
- Unless you can see something,
which we now know you can't,

38:44.322 --> 38:45.975
I'd step back from this one.

38:46.019 --> 38:49.239
- How'd you know
the magic story, Cole?

38:49.283 --> 38:51.459
Seriously? How?

38:51.503 --> 38:54.201
- I told you.
- No, you didn't.

38:54.244 --> 38:57.073
You're holding something back,
just like I was.

38:57.117 --> 38:57.944
- No, I'm not.

38:57.987 --> 39:00.338
- Yeah, you are.
I know you.

39:00.381 --> 39:01.556
- What is this?

39:01.600 --> 39:04.385
- Cole, you should tell them.

39:04.429 --> 39:05.604
- Tell them what?

39:05.647 --> 39:07.040
- What is she talking about?

39:07.083 --> 39:08.737
- I am dying.

39:11.131 --> 39:13.089
Splinter radiation.

39:13.133 --> 39:15.570
Project Charon.

39:15.614 --> 39:18.791
We've all been here
on borrowed time.

39:18.834 --> 39:21.359
And we must return it.

39:21.402 --> 39:23.448
I before you.

39:23.491 --> 39:27.713
But it's as it's meant to be.

39:27.756 --> 39:30.498
Mothers before their children.

39:30.542 --> 39:33.762
♪♪

39:33.806 --> 39:38.201
All of us here
have been something that...

39:38.245 --> 39:41.117
that I once shunned,

39:41.161 --> 39:44.599
something that I can
no longer live without.

39:46.471 --> 39:47.994
Family.

39:48.037 --> 39:52.302
♪♪

39:52.346 --> 39:54.653
I've only one dying wish.

39:58.265 --> 40:00.485
Let's act as one.

40:00.528 --> 40:07.187
♪♪

40:07.230 --> 40:09.711
- The story came
from a woman named Marion.

40:09.755 --> 40:12.845
♪♪

40:15.543 --> 40:17.589
She was my mother.

40:17.632 --> 40:20.592
[mysterious music]

40:20.635 --> 40:27.903
♪♪

40:49.664 --> 40:50.970
- This should work,

40:51.013 --> 40:52.537
get us back up and running.

40:52.580 --> 40:53.973
- What have I always told you

40:54.016 --> 40:57.237
is at the core of every
great achievement?

40:57.280 --> 40:59.021
- Failure.

40:59.065 --> 41:02.895
- Are you here to help
or just to taunt me with coffee?

41:02.938 --> 41:04.549
- I'm simply here
to remind you

41:04.592 --> 41:08.248
that when the day is done
and the sun has set,

41:08.291 --> 41:10.772
come home.

41:10.816 --> 41:15.429
[soft dramatic music]

41:15.473 --> 41:16.735
[keyboard clacking]

41:16.778 --> 41:19.433
- [sighs]

41:19.477 --> 41:21.391
[whooshing]

41:21.435 --> 41:25.265
[machine whirring]

41:25.308 --> 41:28.747
The readings are stable.

41:28.790 --> 41:30.009
Well done.

41:32.577 --> 41:33.665
[alarm beeping]
Whoa, whoa.

41:33.708 --> 41:35.449
Whoa, whoa, whoa, whoa, whoa.

41:35.493 --> 41:36.798
[whirring fades]

41:36.842 --> 41:37.843
Okay.
- Oh.

41:37.886 --> 41:39.932
- Uh...
[chuckles]

41:39.975 --> 41:43.196
So objects either
go forwards or backwards

41:43.239 --> 41:45.372
but never the duplication
of the one.

41:45.415 --> 41:47.940
Never bypass that safeguard.

41:47.983 --> 41:50.508
Basically, given enough power,
it'd be about the fastest way

41:50.551 --> 41:52.335
to rip open a hole
in the universe.

41:52.379 --> 41:53.815
In theory.

41:53.859 --> 41:55.513
Let's not test that theory.

41:55.556 --> 41:56.514
- I'm sorry.

41:56.557 --> 41:58.298
- Ah, don't be.

41:58.341 --> 42:01.257
You know, Emma, this research,

42:01.301 --> 42:03.912
it's ours to start.

42:03.956 --> 42:06.219
It's gonna be yours to finish.

42:06.262 --> 42:11.616
♪♪

42:11.659 --> 42:13.661
[door creaks]

42:26.021 --> 42:29.155
[foreboding music]

42:29.198 --> 42:36.249
♪♪

42:55.921 --> 42:57.444
[whooshing]

42:57.487 --> 42:59.185
♪♪

42:59.228 --> 43:02.623
- I know
how to complete Titan,

43:02.667 --> 43:04.625
how to fulfill its purpose.

43:04.669 --> 43:08.281
♪♪

43:08.324 --> 43:10.588
- And yours.

43:10.631 --> 43:12.372
- Yes.

43:12.415 --> 43:14.243
- Then begin...

43:14.287 --> 43:18.552
so together,
you and I shall have forever

43:18.596 --> 43:21.120
in the forest of red.

43:22.600 --> 43:26.691
- I want nothing more...

43:26.734 --> 43:28.910
Mother.
